{"/service/ndnp/arhi/batch_arhi_dioptase_ver02/data/sn92050145/00516990351/1930103101/0733.xml":{"full_text":"Of the American Federation of Labor\nIn Business Ktfival Beginning\nFor the first time in many\nmonths business opportunity U\nopening. Fundamental adjustments\nhave been made, favorable signs\nare appearing. Our foreign trade\nshows signs of improving, whole\nsale prices are more stable, retail\nprices are down nearer the point\nwhere workers can buy, the outlook\nfor employment is better and that\nmeans increased workers\u2019 buying\npower. Stores see their customers\ncoming back. Opportunity is here\n..have YOII\u00bb\nseen Little Rock\u2019s newest\nand smartest shop\nfor women?\nCome and \u201cvisit with us!\u201d Our beautiful Lounge,\nlocated on the second floor, is a delightful place to\nstop and rest, meet your friends or make engage\nments. There is a telephone, writing desk, rest\nroom, and other conveniences, and wc will be de\nlighted to see you!\nj. t t \u2014y\u2014y.\nt rnrnrrni\nTin\nFROLIC\n\u25a0l-M-l-l-H I COMPANY\n*414 MAIN TK E E 7\nLITTLE ROCK, ARKANSAS\nSee Atlas\u2014\n\u2014Whenever you need money\nto carry out your\nfinancial plans\nClear up your potty accounts\u2014the little amounts\nhere and there\u2014with a loan from Atlas Finance\nCompany. Have one easily paid loan instead of\nseveral that are hard to pay!\nRead How Simple It Is to\nBorrow From Atlas\u2014\nWhen you borrow, wo insure your loan against your\ndeath, or total and permanent disability. In addi\ntion, if you repay the loan in less than 12 months\nwe refund the unused portion of your interest. Nc\nred tape\u2014no embarrassment.\nATLAS FINANCE\nCOMPANY\nAuthorized Capital\n..in.. i\u2014,\u25a0\u25a0\u25a0\u201e\u201e $150,000.00\n107 West Third Street\nfor those who are ready to make\nI the best of it.\nBut business men generally are\nnot ready to nurse seasonal buying\ninto a stable advance. In their fear\nof accumulating inventories, reviv\ning business finds them unprepar\ned. Customers this fall found many\na shelf empty, sizes missing, in\ncomplete lines, #poor selections.\nMerchants admitted they lost\nmany sales for lack of goods. Man\nufacturers likewise are inclined to\nwatch and wait, remembering the\neasy profits of last year.\nInaction will not bring revival.\nWe need intelligent leadership. We\ncan either muddle along and let\nthis depression drag through the\nwinter months or we can build up\na market for our goods and short\nen the road to revival. Plenty of\ngood business is waiting for those\nwho go out for it with foresight\nand initiative.\nAggressive Leadership Needed\nThe high point of fall activity in\nbusiness is still four weeks away.\nThe course of business in the com\ning four weeks will determine the\nprospects for next winter. If we\nwant to avoid a winter like last\nyear\u2019s we must plan for it now by\nu.>ing every intelligent means of\npromoting business revival.\nOne paramount need is consumer\nbuying. All eyes are on the retail\nmarket Storekeepers, wholesalers,\njobbers are waiting for signs of\nbetter buying before they will take\nthe risk of ordering ahead. But\nworkers without Income cannot\nbuy. Increasing employment a n <1\n.sustained wage levels are essential.\nA dangerous tendency n o w\nthreatens the prospect for better\nment. Wage cuts have increased in\nthe past two months. In July, ac\ncording to reports to the Depart\nment of Labor, 20,000 workers\nwere forced to take wage reduc\ntion*\u2014double the number in any\nprevious month .since depression\nbegan. In August the number ros.*\nagain to 24,700 ami cuts average I\n10.5 per cent\u2014the highest yet.\nThis destruction of buying power\nmust be checked if \"e are to go\nforward. Wage earner buying pow\ner is the key to prosperity.\nBusiness men can hasten revival\nand improve tneir own trade with\nj out undue risk by such policies as\nthese: 1. Order ahead; start to\nwork up a normal spring supply. 2.\n(\u2019lit overhead costs (without re\nducing wages) by improving equip\nment und eliminating waste. 3. Im\nprove quality of product and re\nduce prices. 4. Stimulate trade by\nadvertising and special efforts.\nThese measures will increase em\nployment and put products within\nreach of this year\u2019s low incomes\nWage earners can help produce\nbetter articles at lower cost by ini- j\nproving the quality of their work;\nand increasing efficiency. i\nWill revival gain strergth this j\nfall The answer is in the hands j\nof the country\u2019s business leaders.\nI rail Activity Starts\nBetter employment in th first\nj weeks of September is a most en\ncouraging sign. Our figures for\nunemployment of union numbers\nregistered the gain and showed\nthat only 21 per cent were out of\nj work as compared to 22 per cent\nin July and August. Thrmgh July\nand August it holds the same lugh\nI level as in February last winter,\nj but falls in September to per\nt ent. Fven this small improvement\ni is encouraging.\nFmployment gains. though\nsmall, were quite general. Metal\nj trades and street cars were the\nonly groups to register worse con\nditions. In metal trades the number\nout of work increased from 20 to\nWe Say It With Values\nGreater than Ever Before!\nSAVINGS of 25fj to 50f,\nOn Nev Fall and Winter Merchandise\nEverthing for Every Member\noi the Family\nPFEIFER\u2019S GREATEST\n65th Anniversary Sale\n23 per cent. But this was to be ex\npected with the dullness this year\nm metal industries. The number\nout of work in building decreased\nfrom 39,to 38 per cent; in printing\ntrades, employment was generally\nbetter except in New York, but\nthe figures shows 8 per cent still\nout of work. In clothing trades, 18\nper cent of those unemployed in\nA ugust went back to their jobs and\nthere were gains also in theaters,\nmanufacturing, trade and service\nindustries, and among musicians\nFart time work is still prevalent in\nsome industries.\nWith better employment and\nmore buying at stores, business\ngained steadily in the first week\nof September. The volume of bus\niness transacted, as shown by\ncheck payments at banks outside\nNew York, was 13 per cent above\nthe August low. in the second week j\nof September, as shown by car-!\nloads of merchandise shipped on\nthe railroads. But the fourth week\ntn September has not been equal\nto the first three, and with this\ndrop back, talk of gloom and cau\ntion is again being heard.\nManufacturing.\u2014Gains in retail\ntrade have not been accompanied\nby gains in basic manufacture. Au\ntomobile manufacturers are hold- j\ning production closely down to\nsales, with no effort to produce 1\nahead for the spring trade naxt\nyear. September production will\nprobably not be above the August\nlow point and may be still lower.\nIn steel some customers of steel\nproducts are buying ahead for the\nrest of this year and they have\nstimulated steel production in spite\nof the lack of automobile and rail\nroad orders. Steel production in\ncreased from 58 per cent of capac\nity to 01 per cent in the third\nweek in September. Textile mills\narc more active than for some\ntime past.\nFigures for September arc not\nyet out for manufacturing as a\nwhole, but the August figures\nshowed that with the extreme dull\nness in August production failed\nto make the usual seasonal gain.\nIndicators of general trade activ\nity still run about 15 per cent be\nlow normal.\nHuiloin\u2014Contracts awarded in\nSeptember (first three weeks) hold\nthe same level as August. This is\ndisappointing as building usually\nimproves in the fall busy season.\nHut a bright spot in the outlook\nis the gain in residential building\nthis month for homes and apart\nmeits are the back bone of the in\ndustry.\nFarmers.\u2014The scare from large\nsales of Russian wheat on the Chi\ncago exchange last week brought\nprices of grain and cotton to the\nlowest level in fifteen years. If\nthese low prices were to last, farm\ners would suffer serious hardships.\nHut gradual improvement seems\nlikely. For our corn crop is 229\nmillion bushels short from the\ndrought, and foreign countries can\nnot supply us since the world crop\nin five countries is 15 pe^ cent be\nlow last year. Farmers will prob\nably have to use wheat for feed by\nmid-winter. Shire 'he world wh at\ncrop (Department of Agriculture\nestimate) is only 3.4 per cent above\nlast year, or 79 million bushels, it\nseems likely that there will not be\ntoo much. Demand will probably\nraise prices, though observers be\nlieve gains will be slow.\nCost of Living Lower\nCost of living in August was 6.7\nper cent lower than August last\nyear. But the decline has been less\nthan half the drop in wholesale\nprices which are 14 per cent below\nlast August. The cost of living line\nhas gone down so slowly that wage\nearners have not had the full bene\nfit of lower wholesale prices. For\ninstance, most wage earners find\nbread no cheaper, though the\nwholesale price of grain is more\nthan 22 per cent below last year.\nIn business depressions, retail\nprices usually go down last and\nleast.\nIn August, the downward course\nfor wholesale prices was checked,\nand the line runs straight for a\nmonth with prices at the same\nlevel. This is a most encouraging\nsign, for a check in the decline will\nprobably be taken as a signal for\nmanufacturers to buy the mate\nrials they need and their orders\nwill stimulate activity. The lower\nlevel of living costs is also encour\naging for workers can buy more\nWhen incomes are not increasing.\nliving' costa must be cut to allow\nworkers to buy and stimulate re\ncovery.\nAgain in August wage cutting\nhas increased; 184 firms reporting\nto the Department of Labor cut\nwages, as compared to 117 in July.\nN'o wage increases were reported\nin August.\nThe trend toward wage cuts has\ngained force rapidly since March\nand in July and August has reach\ned alarming proportions. In the\nfirst month of depression wage\ncuts were held down as a result\nof President Hoover\u2019s conferences\nThe line keeps a low level till\nMarch. Then small firms began to\ncut and now larger firms too have\njoined the movement.\nA more pernicious influence on\nthe present precarious business\nsituation could hardly be found. A\nworker who can buy more than his\nabsolute seeds is a force for re\nvival. Cut his income and you j\nmake him a force for depression. I\nSTOCK MARKET PLOT\nAIDED BY JOBLESS\nPhiladelphia. The prosperity\nLoom launched by clever publicity\nagents of the Victor Talking Ma-\nc'rine Corporation, Camden. N. J., j\nve? a plot to boost the price of\nftock of this corporation, that \u201cin\nHarvey Shofner 1\nfor\nCity Treasurer\nwill appreciate your vote\nand influence.\nHe ha-s been a resident of\nLittle Rock for more than j\n20 years and never before I\nasked for any public office;\nbut is now opposed by the\npresent treasurer who has\nheld this office for two\nterms and is seeking a\nthird (3rd) term.\nHARVEY SHOFNER CANDIDATE\nfor\nCITY TREASURER\n\"LET\u2019S BE CONSISTENT\u201d Mr\nHOT OR COLD\nRAIN OR SHINE\u2014\nThe Year-\u2019Round Drink\nfor HEALTH!\n\u2014at 10, 2 and 4 o\u2019clock\nLittle Rock Bottling: Co.\n1107 AV 7th.\u2014Phone 4-1469\nCohn\u2019s\n\u201cWeek of Sales\u201d\nNow In Progress\nThis will be a week of intensive value giving not an underselling\nevent. We do not seek to undersell we try to overgive more\nstyle, more quality, more value than your money would buy ordi\nnarily. Instead of taking out value to meet a price, we put in extra\nvalue. You can buy with the same assurance of complete satisfac\ntion that you have always had in merchandise from this store.\nNew Offerings Every Day\u2014\nWatch the Daily Papers!\nm.m\nn company\nITT*.* ROCK\nsi aers\u201d could unload, according to\nthe Philadelphia Union Labor Rec\nord.\nThe plants .were opened a month\na go with bands and red fire,\nj \u201cStorehouses in Camden and this\ncity,\u201d gays the labor editor, \u201care\nrapidly being filled and